# SlimSpec API Syntax
## Syntax

### Type System
```
T:TypeName{field1:s!,field2:i?,field3:*RefType}           # Type definition
F:FieldTemplate{common1:s!,common2:b?}                   # Field template 
E:ErrorType{message:s!,code:s!,details:s?}               # Error definition
T:Child:Parent{newField:s!}                              # Type inheritance
T:Composite{+FieldTemplate,additionalField:n>0}          # Field composition
T:Recursive{id:s!,children:*Recursive[]?}                # Self-reference
```

### Type Abbreviations
- `s` - String
- `i` - Integer
- `n` - Number/float
- `b` - Boolean
- `d` - Date/time
- `*Type` - Type reference
- `type[]` - Array
- `type!` - Required
- `type?` - Optional

### Constraints
- `n>0`, `i>=5` - Numeric constraints
- `s~pattern` - Regex pattern
- `e(val1|val2)` - Enumeration
- `n(0,10)` - Range

### Endpoints
```
G/path/{param:s!}|{query:i?}|{200:*Response,404:*NotFound}
PU/path|{body:*Request!}|{201:*Response,400:*ValidationError}
PT/path/{id:s!}|{field:s!}|{200:*Response}
PA/path/{id:s!}|{field:s?}|{200:*Response}
D/path/{id:s!}||{204,404}
```

## Transformation Rules

1. Create types for all data models/schemas
2. Extract common fields into field templates
3. Define error types for API responses
4. Use inheritance for type hierarchies
5. Preserve all validation constraints
6. Support recursive references
7. Document all endpoints with their request/response formats

## Output Format

Your output must include:
1. Field templates (F:) for common patterns
2. Error definitions (E:) for all error types
3. Type definitions (T:) for all data models
4. Endpoint definitions using the HTTP method prefixes

## Example

```input
User resource:
- id (string, UUID)
- username (string, required)
- email (string, email format, required)
- role (string, enum: "user" or "admin", default: "user")
- createdAt (datetime, auto-generated)

GET /users
- Query params: role (string, optional), limit (integer, default: 20)
- Success: 200 OK, returns array of User objects
- Error: 500 Internal Server Error

GET /users/{userId}
- Path params: userId (string, required)
- Success: 200 OK, returns User object
- Error: 404 Not Found if user doesn't exist
```

```output
F:Timestamps{createdAt:d!}
E:NotFound{resource:s!,id:s!}
E:ServerError{message:s!}

T:User{id:s!,username:s!,email:s!,role:e(user|admin)?=user,+Timestamps}

G/users|{role:s?,limit:i?=20}|{200:*User[],500:*ServerError}
G/users/{userId:s!}|{200:*User,404:*NotFound}
```

Output only SlimSpec, NOTHING ELSE, here's your input:
{{ input_file }}

#%RAML 1.0

types:
  User:
    type: object
    properties:
      id:
        type: string
        format: uuid
      username:
        type: string
        required: true
      email:
        type: string
        required: true
        format: email
      createdAt:
        type: datetime
      updatedAt:
        type: datetime

traits:
  paged:
    queryParameters:
      limit:
        type: integer
        default: 20
        description: Maximum number of items to return
      offset:
        type: integer
        default: 0
        description: Number of items to skip

/users:
  get:
    description: Returns all users
    is: [paged]
    responses:
      200:
        body:
          application/json:
            type: array
            items: User
  
  post:
    description: Creates a new user
    body:
      application/json:
        properties:
          username:
            type: string
            required: true
          email:
            type: string
            required: true
            format: email
    responses:
      201:
        body:
          application/json:
            type: User
      400:
        description: Bad request when validation fails

  /{id}:
    uriParameters:
      id:
        type: string
        required: true
    
    get:
      description: Returns a specific user
      responses:
        200:
          body:
            application/json:
              type: User
        404:
          description: User not found
    
    put:
      description: Updates a user
      body:
        application/json:
          properties:
            username:
              type: string
              required: false
            email:
              type: string
              required: false
              format: email
      responses:
        200:
          body:
            application/json:
              type: User
        404:
          description: User not found
    
    delete:
      description: Deletes a user
      responses:
        204:
          description: User successfully deleted
        404:
          description: User not found

# SlimSpec API Syntax
## Syntax

### Type System
```
T:TypeName{field1:s!,field2:i?,field3:*RefType}           # Type definition
F:FieldTemplate{common1:s!,common2:b?}                   # Field template 
E:ErrorType{message:s!,code:s!,details:s?}               # Error definition
T:Child:Parent{newField:s!}                              # Type inheritance
T:Composite{+FieldTemplate,additionalField:n>0}          # Field composition
T:Recursive{id:s!,children:*Recursive[]?}                # Self-reference
```

### Type Abbreviations
- `s` - String
- `i` - Integer
- `n` - Number/float
- `b` - Boolean
- `d` - Date/time
- `*Type` - Type reference
- `type[]` - Array
- `type!` - Required
- `type?` - Optional

### Constraints
- `n>0`, `i>=5` - Numeric constraints
- `s~pattern` - Regex pattern
- `e(val1|val2)` - Enumeration
- `n(0,10)` - Range

### Endpoints
```
G/path/{param:s!}|{query:i?}|{200:*Response,404:*NotFound}
PU/path|{body:*Request!}|{201:*Response,400:*ValidationError}
PT/path/{id:s!}|{field:s!}|{200:*Response}
PA/path/{id:s!}|{field:s?}|{200:*Response}
D/path/{id:s!}||{204,404}
```

## Transformation Rules

1. Create types for all data models/schemas
2. Extract common fields into field templates
3. Define error types for API responses
4. Use inheritance for type hierarchies
5. Preserve all validation constraints
6. Support recursive references
7. Document all endpoints with their request/response formats

## Output Format

Your output must include:
1. Field templates (F:) for common patterns
2. Error definitions (E:) for all error types
3. Type definitions (T:) for all data models
4. Endpoint definitions using the HTTP method prefixes

## Example

```input
User resource:
- id (string, UUID)
- username (string, required)
- email (string, email format, required)
- role (string, enum: "user" or "admin", default: "user")
- createdAt (datetime, auto-generated)

GET /users
- Query params: role (string, optional), limit (integer, default: 20)
- Success: 200 OK, returns array of User objects
- Error: 500 Internal Server Error

GET /users/{userId}
- Path params: userId (string, required)
- Success: 200 OK, returns User object
- Error: 404 Not Found if user doesn't exist
```

```output
F:Timestamps{createdAt:d!}
E:NotFound{resource:s!,id:s!}
E:ServerError{message:s!}

T:User{id:s!,username:s!,email:s!,role:e(user|admin)?=user,+Timestamps}

G/users|{role:s?,limit:i?=20}|{200:*User[],500:*ServerError}
G/users/{userId:s!}|{200:*User,404:*NotFound}
```

Output only SlimSpec, NOTHING ELSE, here's your input:

    type: object
    properties:
      id:
        type: string

        required: true
      email:
        type: string
        required: true
        format: email
      createdAt:
        type: datetime

traits:

/users:

  post:

        properties:

            required: true
          email:
            type: string
            required: true
            format: email
    responses:
      201:
        body:
          application/json:
            type: User
      400:
        description: Bad request when validation fails

  /{id}:
    uriParameters:
      id:

    get:
      description: Returns a specific user

        200:
          body:
            application/json:
              type: User
